Invoking: `validate` with `{'patch': '--- a/Zend/zend_vm_execute.h\n+++ b/Zend/zend_vm_execute.h\n@@ -55852,6 +55852,10 @@\n \tLOAD_OPLINE();\n+\tif (UNEXPECTED(OPLINE == NULL)) {\n+\t\treturn;\n+\t}\n \tZEND_VM_LOOP_INTERRUPT_CHECK();\n'}`
responded: The repeated failures indicate that the dereference of `OPLINE->handler` is still happening even after the check, likely due to macro expansion or the structure of the conditional compilation. The correct and robust fix is to check for `OPLINE == NULL` immediately after `LOAD_OPLINE()` and before entering the loop, so that the loop is never entered if `OPLINE` is NULL.

**Patch:**
Insert the check right after `LOAD_OPLINE();` and before `ZEND_VM_LOOP_INTERRUPT_CHECK();` and the loop.

```diff
--- a/Zend/zend_vm_execute.h
+++ b/Zend/zend_vm_execute.h
@@ -55852,6 +55852,10 @@
 	LOAD_OPLINE();
+	if (UNEXPECTED(OPLINE == NULL)) {
+		return;
+	}
 	ZEND_VM_LOOP_INTERRUPT_CHECK();
```

This will prevent the loop and any dereference from happening if `OPLINE` is NULL at the start.

Let's validate this patch.

